**Clinical Reasoning:**
The patient has unilateral scrotal pain, dysuria, and urinary frequency—classic features of epididymitis or epididymoorchitis. While the urethral swab showed no organisms via Gram stain and there was no discharge, the presence of 3 WBC/Hpf on urinalysis suggests pyuria. Importantly, chlamydia is a leading cause of non-gonococcal urethritis and epididymitis in young men, especially without overt discharge. Unlike gonorrhea, chlamydia often presents with dysuria and mild or absent discharge, and its diagnosis relies heavily on urinalysis and PCR testing rather than visible discharge. Additionally, testicular ultrasound revealing increased vascularity supports inflammation consistent with infective causes.

